386→                        <div id="content">Let $a_0=0$ and $a_1=1$, and in general define $a_k$ to be the least integer $&#62;a_{k-1}$ for which $(n-a_k,n-a_i)=1$ for all $0\leq i&#60;k$. Does\[\sum_{0&#60;a_i&#60; n}\frac{1}{a_i}\to \infty\]as $n\to \infty$? What about if we restrict the sum to those $i$ such that $n-a_j$ is divisible by some prime $\leq a_j$, or the complement of such $i$?</div>
387→                        <div id="problem_id"><a href="/460">#460</a>: <a href="#cite-Er77c-460" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er77c','460'); return false;">[Er77c,p.64]</a><a href="#cite-ErGr80-460" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGr80','460'); return false;">[ErGr80,p.91]</a></div>
